<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/70567089-peter"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/70567089-peter">Peter</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    The detective says something to Oliver at one point, along the lines of the, I think the thing he (James) most liked about you was that you liked him.<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    The detective says something to Oliver at one point, along the lines of the, I think the thing he (James) most liked about you was that you liked him. Actors have to master the art of deception and manipulation, Oliver was clearly the most manipulated, partly through choice, and James was the prime manipulator. He removed his chief rival in Richard and allowed Oliver to take the rap for him. Through his actions with Wren and Meredith, he also sought to undermine any connection they might develop with Oliver. In effect, he's a more presentable version of Richard. Whether he took his own life or faked his death (I'd favour the latter), his intention was to maintain his sway over Oliver. I'd suggest the main object of James' love is ultimately himself.<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
