    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2801384916" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2801384916" />
    <a title="C.G. Drews" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11375137-c-g-drews"><img alt="C.G. Drews" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521552918p2/11375137.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2801384916?book_show_action=true">Aug 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="C.G. Drews" class="user" itemprop="url" name="C.G. Drews" href="/user/show/11375137-c-g-drews">C.G. Drews</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=5-star">5-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=read-2019">read-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=dark-academia">dark-academia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=read-2021">read-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=adult">adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11375137-c-g-drews?shelf=reread">reread</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2801384916" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2760847426846909198"><b>[read 2 | june 2021]</b><br/>Absolutely chose to reread this to suffer and I am glad I did 😪The reread was fantastic, loved it so deeply (although a little less than the first time because I&apos;ve read dark academia books I liked better since 2019) but the audiobook was a fantastic choice because listening to Shakespeare hit different. I just am here for poetically tragic books and this one has such a love for words, for reality told through a difference lens, for tight friendship groups and complicated, me</span>
  <span id="freeText2760847426846909198" style="display:none"><b>[read 2 | june 2021]</b><br />Absolutely chose to reread this to suffer and I am glad I did 😪The reread was fantastic, loved it so deeply (although a little less than the first time because I've read dark academia books I liked better since 2019) but the audiobook was a fantastic choice because listening to Shakespeare hit different. I just am here for poetically tragic books and this one has such a love for words, for reality told through a difference lens, for tight friendship groups and complicated, messy and often toxic love. I think about it too much 😭.<br /><br /><br /><b>[read 1 | august 2019]</b><br />This book is just <i>that good</i> that I'm having a total overwrought and overwhelmed breakdown. I was just...so so into it. I can't breeeeathe anymore. And I freaking swear; i was about to slam this book so hard across the room and sob in despair and not even rate it -- but the ending. The last fcking sentence. I am a pile of unorganised emotions in a trench coat just...just go. I'll be fine.<br /><br /><br /><b>"Imagine having all your own thoughts and feelings tangled up with all the thoughts and feelings of a whole other person. It can be hard, sometimes, to sort out which is which.” </b><br />not only is the book an engaging and compelling and all-consuming story about characters; it also really delves into the greyness of becoming so in-tune with your art, you don't know where it ends and you begin. It's specifically about actors, but I can definitely see how this bleeds into all types of artistry. And oh wow did these kids lose it. So so much. The story is a spiral of losing yourself and facing reality. All seven of them preferred books and plays, art and poetry, to reality and they were very ill equip to handle tragedy that wasn't part of a script. <br /><br />I love books about monstrous things happening to not-monstrous people and then seeing how they react. <br /><br /><br /><b>// “We had, like seven siblings, spent so much time together that we had seen the best and worst of one another and were unimpressed by either.”</b><br />The characters though...<i>the characters</i>. I don't even know what to SAY except vague sobbing. There are 7 of them and I withered inside originally because I'm not good with huge casts (I have the memory of a moth eaten coat) but they all just stood off the page as whole people, complex and mysterious and enigmas, easily and fast. <br /><br />// Oliver narrates; he's the good boy, nice and naive and not quite a good enough actor, but the one who takes up the slack. He is also super gay and super has no idea.<br />// Richard is the leader; the hero, the strongest and therefore the cruellest. he is slowly warping into this horrible person, toxic and frightening<br />// Meredith is the beauty; the one who gets cast as the beautiful woman, the temptress and seductress. she's hates that people don't see past her beautiful body.<br />// Alexander is the resident gay disaster; drug addict to cope and likes to flirt with boys who don't realise they're gay until ~Alexander~ appears. He is "sexually amphibious" which is a beautiful term ok will stan. He is also a creature of dark corners and vulnerabilities.<br />// Filippa, the mystery; she's the background character who gets forgotten and cast to the smallest rolls despite her being quite talented, she's not bold enough. Her life is a mystery and it's never quite unravelled, except she sticks with Oliver through the whole ordeal (despite them not seeming like super close buddies during uni)<br />// Wren was probably the weakest and most delicate; "Richard's cousin" was her main identifier tbh.<br />// James, oh James, I cry; delicate and extraordinarily talented, often the villain caste type and always the one people are drawn to. He and Oliver are roommates ("THEY WERE ONLY ROOMMATES") and their sexual tension is terrible and beautiful. James should be protected at all costs.<br /><br />I loved the characters; they were awful sometimes and self involved others and they were a mess of pretentiousness and vulnerabilities that they hid behind their acting. <br /><br />It is a queer story but it is more about denying that part of you because of fear. (I kind of wish it had been gayer but you know; 10/10 would smack both those boys heads together i cAN'T BELIEVE THEY TREATED EACH OTHER THAT WAY.)<br /><br /><b>// “One sin, I know, another doth provoke; Murder’s as near to lust as flame to smoke.”</b><br />Look I call it: it's a pretentious story. There is SO much Shakespeare in it and do you want to know how much Shakespeare I know??? n o n e. Yet it kind of made me in love with the concept, even if I still don't really understand the core and lines of that style of poetry and plays. It was intoxicating the way the story unravelled, because at times it felt so aesthetic and slow and homey...and it focused on the tight tangle of emotions and how your 20s is such a time of turmoil as well as growth. They're young, about 20-21 I think? And there is jealousy. There are mistakes. There are threats. There is murder. There is brokenness. Guilt.<br /><br />And it begins with Oliver in jail.<br /><br /><br /><b>This book simultaneously inspires and levels me. </b>I wanted more from it in several places, about several things, but mostly I'm just here to be tortured by soft dramatic theatre kid sand their terrible disaster life decisions while half of everyone is extremely suppressing their queerness and the other half is extremely suppressing trauma. I nearly hated it; but then I loved it so fiercely.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2760847426846909198" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


