<div id="review_2778443027" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2778443027" />
    <a title="Amy Imogene Reads" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84702001-amy-imogene-reads"><img alt="Amy Imogene Reads" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548082309p2/84702001.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2778443027?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy Imogene Reads" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy Imogene Reads" href="/user/show/84702001-amy-imogene-reads">Amy Imogene Reads</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781250095299" href="/book/show/34275217-if-we-were-villains">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=adult-fiction">adult-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=read-in-2019">read-in-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/84702001-amy-imogene-reads?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2778443027" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4022704161090383897">5 sonnet-inspiring stars<br/><br/><b>An anti-Shakespeare reader reads a book structured, centered, and deeply versed in Shakespeare...and literally falls head over heels for it?</b> <i>If We Were Villains</i> was amazing. <br/><br/><b>Writing:</b> ★★★★★<br/><b>Structure:</b> ★★★★★<br/><b>Characters:</b> ★★★★★<br/><b>Pacing:</b> ★★★★★<br/><br/><b>Seven senior year college students</b> at an intense fine arts conservatory in Illinois <b>find themselves in their own version of a Shakespearean tragedy</b> as real life begins to blur around the edges of Shakespeare&apos;s verse. <b>The hero, the villain, th</b></span>
  <span id="freeText4022704161090383897" style="display:none">5 sonnet-inspiring stars<br /><br /><b>An anti-Shakespeare reader reads a book structured, centered, and deeply versed in Shakespeare...and literally falls head over heels for it?</b> <i>If We Were Villains</i> was amazing. <br /><br /><b>Writing:</b> ★★★★★<br /><b>Structure:</b> ★★★★★<br /><b>Characters:</b> ★★★★★<br /><b>Pacing:</b> ★★★★★<br /><br /><b>Seven senior year college students</b> at an intense fine arts conservatory in Illinois <b>find themselves in their own version of a Shakespearean tragedy</b> as real life begins to blur around the edges of Shakespeare's verse. <b>The hero, the villain, the tyrant, the ingenue, the temptress, the extra.</b> <br /><br /><b>Who plays who, and when, and why?</b> <br /><br /><i>What happens when you become immersed into your role?</i><br /><br />Oliver Marks has just spent 10 years in prison for a murder he may or may not have committed. He's never revealed the truth - until now. Voicing his story to the primary case detective in an off-the-record interview on the site of the crime, <b>Oliver recounts his tragedy in the structure of Shakespeare—in 5 Acts.</b><br /><br /><b>I was hooked by this.</b><br /><br />It is technically Oliver's point of view, but the story unfolds in almost third-person narration as the events of the group's fourth year unravel in atmospheric detail. <b>There is the perfect amount of foreshadowing</b> from Oliver—one liners that allude to future events, etc.—<b>but for the most part, we're living the year alongside the students</b> in real time. <br /><br />One of <i>If We Were Villains</i>'s main selling points is its claustrophobic and almost familial approach to its primary cast of characters. <b>Evoking the unique collegiate mindset of the "found family" friend group in close proximity,</b> the cast of main characters feels disturbingly entwined, and causes deep set emotions to bubble to the surface as the seven work, live, practice, sleep, and act together as one (fractured) unit. <br /><br />I won't go into the seven's individual roles in the book, as part of the fun is immediate internal typecasting and subsequent role shifts that occur naturally. Suffice to say, it's obvious that <b>all is not as it initially appears.</b> <br /><br /><i>If We Were Villains</i> is a one of a kind adventure with a truly unforgettable cast. <b>You'll think about these characters long after you close the book.</b> If you're a fan of the theater, I imagine this is an easy sell. I was not (and still am not) a theater person. But <b><i>If We Were Villains</i> transcends its typecasting</b> and has an appeal for all, not just those who can smell paint on the stage sets. <b>This crime could have happened elsewhere, but it is best shown in its purest habitat—the theater.</b> <br /><br />If I had to pick a negative, <b>the characters' penchant for speaking in snippets of Shakespearean verse was hard to pick up at first...and I'll be the first to admit that occasionally, I skimmed those dialogue chunks.</b> Shakespeare is definitely a living, breathing entity in these characters lives, and <b>in order to dive deep into their story you must dive deep into the Shakespeare they surround themselves with</b>. It's a lot to take in at the beginning, but as you spiral down into the plot it almost (okay, not quite) disappears into the background. <br /><br /><b>This is a strong contender for my favorite fiction (mystery?) of all time.</b> Recommended for anyone who enjoys entangled plot lines with close friend groups, theater-inspired stories, the Bard (of course), and viciously emotionally-motivated crimes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4022704161090383897" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


