  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2985612230" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2985612230" />
    <a title="Susan&#39;s Reviews" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19736308-susan-s-reviews"><img alt="Susan&#39;s Reviews" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507651790p2/19736308.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2985612230?book_show_action=true">Sep 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan&#39;s Reviews" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan&#39;s Reviews" href="/user/show/19736308-susan-s-reviews">Susan&#39;s Reviews</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2985612230" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10767025116295816865"><b>Where you able to decipher the clues in James&apos; last note to Oliver?</b><br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1595602613ra/29858951.gif' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><u>If We Were Villains</u> is an intelligent, well written theatrical thriller, with lots of emotional and physical drama. This is to be expected of a troupe of American theater students whose main focus is Shakespeare&apos;s works. <br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1618207834ra/31165762.gif' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>The bird&apos;s-eye view of casting and producing one of these dramas was interesting, but I felt distanced by those numerous archaic dramatic passages. And yet, these passages did help set the stage for a dark and he</span>
  <span id="freeText10767025116295816865" style="display:none"><b>Where you able to decipher the clues in James' last note to Oliver?</b><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1595602613ra/29858951.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><u>If We Were Villains</u> is an intelligent, well written theatrical thriller, with lots of emotional and physical drama. This is to be expected of a troupe of American theater students whose main focus is Shakespeare's works. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1618207834ra/31165762.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The bird's-eye view of casting and producing one of these dramas was interesting, but I felt distanced by those numerous archaic dramatic passages. And yet, these passages did help set the stage for a dark and heavy tone: surely "something wicked this way comes!" <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1618207834ra/31165763.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>James aptly warns everyone during one of his dramatic scenes that we are all deceivers on the stage of life and that we are to trust no one. <i>What a tangled web, indeed, when first we practice to deceive.....!</i> (I'm paraphrasing here.) <br><br>I was much struck by Oliver's sacrifice and the surprise twist at the end. But after a while.... I grew dissatisfied. We are given subtle hints that the relationship between Oliver and James is deeper and more involved than mere friendship. Oliver and James might have feelings for one another, but Oliver also has a "thing" for the lovely Meredith. Then James gets passionate with Wren and does a 365 and makes a pass at Meredith. Orgy, anyone?<br><br>Well, not quite, but that was a fair amount of bed-hopping. I was starting to lose track of who was sleeping with whom! And yes, I get that Oliver and James were reacting out of jealousy most of the time, but their reticence seemed unnatural. They were all actors after all, and quite used to exploring the hidden meanings and emotional motivations behind their character's actions and dialogue. (But I get that the story would have been over far too soon had Oliver and James had their "lightbulb" moment earlier in this drama.)<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1618207834ra/31165764.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Too late, Oliver realizes his true feelings for James, which he refused to admit or disclose either out of discomfort or fear of rejection or jealousy. Oliver makes the ultimate sacrifice of his freedom, because he knows he is mentally and emotionally stronger than the others. Finally, to make things even more melodramatic, in the spirit of all Shakespearean tragedies, Oliver discovers, again too late, upon his release from prison that James has drowned himself. Oliver is left bereft, marking time once again in Meredith's bed. <b>Big, big spoiler alert:</b> <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ But Hark, a note! Those two envelopes, penned by James just before his last fateful swim in the frigid waters of the north Pacific ocean, leave a vital clue that only James can decipher. Hope stirs anew in Oliver's grieving heart: James' body was never found - he may well still be alive! <br>The root of my dissatisfaction: Emotionally, I wanted a physical/face to face "closure" scene between Oliver and James (and judging by the many Q &amp; A queries for a sequel to the author, I am not alone in this.) That kiss on the hand was not enough.... But I get that the author wanted her readers to do a bit of homework for the potential HEA. I took comfort from James' quote of a passage from <u>Pericles</u> in his last note to Oliver. At the end of Shakespeare's drama, the main character Pericles is miraculously reunited with Thaisa and Marina (the wife and daughter whom he had mistakenly thought were dead and buried at sea). The fickle hand of Fate, which had parted the happy family, was moved once again to reunite these beleaguered players. <br>A clever use of misapprehension and misdirection! I have no doubt in my mind that the author is hinting at a similar fate for Oliver and James. What do you think?  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br>I would have rated this higher, but the excessive use of direct quotations and excerpts from the various dramas slowed the action down considerably, and interrupted the flow of this novel. I kept pausing to look up the passages and put them into context, which messed with the atmosphere and pacing. (And yes, I studied quite a few of Shakespeare's dramas in high school, and we would often see various productions at our local Stratford Theatre, so I am not unacquainted with his works.) (Note: I have now reread this novel without dwelling on all of the direct quotations, and it was much more enjoyable.) <br>I rate this very well done "intrigue" a 4 out of 5 stars.</["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></span>
  <a data-text-id="10767025116295816865" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


